art` has proper accessibility for list items\n\nLet me also check one important 
thing: In `im.service.ts` `getConversations`, the native SQL query uses `?` plac
eholders which is correct. But the `dataSource.query` returns raw rows where `cr
eated_at` might be a Date object or string depending on the driver. The code doe
s `lastMessage.created_at ? new Date(lastMessage.created_at as string).toISOStri
ng() : ...`. This seems okay.\n\nAnother issue: In `im.service.ts` `getConversat
ions` line 412-424, the native SQL uses `MAX(sequence_id)` and joins on `sequenc
e_id`. Since `sequence_id` is `BIGINT AUTO_INCREMENT`, this is fine. But wait - 
`messageRepo.create` sets `sequence_id: 0` which "Will be replaced by auto-incre
ment". But in TypeORM, when you set `@Generated("increment")` on a regular `@Col
umn`, saving with an explicit value might override the auto-increment. Actually,
TypeORM typically ignores the provided value for auto-increment columns when usi
ng `save()`. But wait - the entity uses `@Column("bigint")` with `@Generated("in
crement")`. In MySQL, `save()` with `sequence_id: 0` might actually insert 0, wh
ich would conflict with the auto-increment. Let me check if this is an issue.\n\
nActually, looking at the TypeORM behavior, `@Generated("increment")` is typical
ly used with `@PrimaryGeneratedColumn`. For non-primary columns, TypeORM might n
ot properly handle it. The migration defines `sequence_id BIGINT NOT NULL AUTO_I
NCREMENT`. In MySQL, only one column per table can be auto-increment, and it mus
t be indexed. The migration shows `sequence_id` has its own index. But TypeORM\'
s `save()` might try to set `sequence_id = 0` explicitly, which could cause issu
es.\n\nWait, let me re-read the entity:\n```typescript\n@Column("bigint")\n@Gene
rated("increment")\nsequence_id: number;\n```\n\nThis should tell TypeORM to let
the database generate the value. When `save()` is called, TypeORM should omit th
e `sequence_id` from the INSERT if it\'s undefined/null/0? Actually, with `@Gene
rated("increment")`, TypeORM typically won\'t include the column in the INSERT s
tatement if the value is `undefined`. But the code explicitly sets `sequence_id:
